<DOC><DOCNO> AP881209-0169 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 2118EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WhizKid-Custody     12-09 0215</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Whiz Kid-Custody,0220</SECOND><HEAD>Prodigy to Live With Mother on Temporary Basis, Investigator Says</HEAD><DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Twelve-year-old college graduateAdragon De Mello, who was taken away from his father in September,will live with his mother on a trial basis beginning this weekend,representatives of both parents said.   Adragon, who is believed to be the country's youngest collegegraduate, was placed in a foster home after his mother alleged thatthe boy and his father had a suicide pact.   Agustin De Mello, 58, the boy's father, said he will contest thecourt's decision. He was arrested in September for investigation offelony child endangerment although no charges have been filed. Hehas denied forming any suicide pact.   The decision by Santa Cruz County Child Protective Services thisweek did not mean that the mother would be given permanent custody,Robert Bortnick, an investigator who works for the father'sattorney, said Thursday.   Officials at the agency refused to discuss the case and the boy'smother, Cathy Gunn, also declined comment. But Gunn's attorney,Patricia Vorreiter, said Thursday that the boy will move to hismother's Santa Clara County home on Saturday.   Adragon graduated from the University of California at Santa Cruzin June, when he was 11. He earned a degree in mathematics.</TEXT></DOC>